# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aeolian-processes
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aeolian-processes/2018-indian-dust-storms] From 2 to 3 May 2018, high-velocity dust storms swept across parts of North India.
[src:aeolian-processes/2018-indian-dust-storms] 125 people died and over 200 were injured.
[src:aeolian-processes/2018-indian-dust-storms] In Uttar Pradesh, 43 died in the city of Agra and about 30 died elsewhere in the state.
[src:aeolian-processes/2018-indian-dust-storms] In neighboring Rajasthan, about 35 people died and over 200 were injured after winds downed more than 8,000 electricity poles and uprooted hundreds of trees.
[src:aeolian-processes/2018-indian-dust-storms] Storms are not uncommon in the region; however, because these storms occurred at night and with greater wind speeds than average (~100 mph), the death toll was higher than usual.
[src:aeolian-processes/2018-indian-dust-storms] Dust storms are a feature of India's seasonal weather patterns.
[src:aeolian-processes/2018-indian-dust-storms] The storms typically occur in the summer months, when the weather has been dry to allow dust to be picked up by passing winds.
[src:aeolian-processes/2018-indian-dust-storms] The dust storm occurred at the start of India's monsoon season.
[src:aeolian-processes/2018-indian-dust-storms] In the days prior, region meteorologists had forecast thunderstorms and high winds to occur over that week.
[src:aeolian-processes/2018-indian-dust-storms] Contributing to the storm was a period of abnormally high temperatures for the region, which increased the intensity of the weather system.
[src:aeolian-processes/2018-indian-dust-storms] The dust storm first started late on 2 May 2018, predominantly hitting the states of Uttar Pradesh and Rajasthan.
[src:aeolian-processes/2018-indian-dust-storms] At least 73 people were killed in Uttar Pradesh, with 43 of those in the city of Agra; 21 people have been reported killed in Kheragarh, a town around 50 km south-west of the city.
[src:aeolian-processes/2018-indian-dust-storms] At least 35 people were killed in Rajasthan, with the Alwar district being the worst hit; the Bharatpur and Dholpur districts were also affected.
[src:aeolian-processes/2018-indian-dust-storms] Four people died in the state of Uttarakhand, and Delhi was also affected.
[src:aeolian-processes/2018-indian-dust-storms] More than 200 people were injured by the storm.
[src:aeolian-processes/2018-indian-dust-storms] Most damage and fatalities were associated with high winds, rather than dust.
[src:aeolian-processes/2018-indian-dust-storms] In Rajasthan, electricity supplies were interrupted by 200–300 downed pylons, and schools were closed in the Alwar district.
[src:aeolian-processes/2018-indian-dust-storms] Because conditions were still prime for more severe weather, the Uttar Pradesh government continued to plan to alert its citizens to weather conditions for the following 48 hours.
[src:aeolian-processes/2018-indian-dust-storms] The Government of Uttar Pradesh has announced compensation for the relatives of those killed amounting to ₹4 lakh (US$4,200).
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] A **four-wheel drive**, also called **4×4** ("four-by-four") or **4WD**, is a two-axled vehicle drivetrain capable of providing torque to all of its wheels simultaneously.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] It may be full-time or on-demand, and is typically linked via a transfer case providing an additional output drive shaft and, in many instances, additional gear ranges.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Four-wheel-drive systems were developed in many different markets and used in many different vehicle platforms.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] There is no universally accepted set of terminology that describes the various architectures and functions.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The terms used by various manufacturers often reflect marketing rather than engineering considerations or significant technical differences between systems.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] SAE International's standard J1952 recommends only the term "all-wheel drive" with additional subclassifications that cover all types of AWD/4WD/4×4 systems found on production vehicles.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] "Four-by-four" or "4×4" is frequently used to refer to a class of vehicles in general.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Syntactically, the first figure indicates the total number of axle ends and the second indicates the number of axle ends that are powered.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Accordingly, 4×2 means a four-wheel vehicle that transmits engine torque to only two axle ends: the front two in front-wheel drive or the rear two in rear-wheel drive.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Similarly, a 6×4 vehicle has three axles, two of which provide torque to two axle ends each.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] If this vehicle were a truck with dual rear wheels on two rear axles, (and thus having ten wheels), its configuration would still be formulated as 6×4.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] During World War II, the U.S. military used spaces and a capital 'X' – as "4 X 2" or "6 X 4".
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Four-wheel drive (4WD) refers to vehicles with two axles providing torque to four axle ends.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] In the North American market, the term generally refers to a system optimized for off-road driving conditions.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The term "4WD" is typically designated for vehicles equipped with a transfer case that switches between 2WD and 4WD operating modes, either manually or automatically.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] All-wheel drive (AWD) was historically synonymous with "four-wheel drive" on four-wheeled vehicles, and six-wheel drive on 6×6s, and so on, being used in that fashion at least as early as the 1920s.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] As of 2026 in North America, the term is applied to both heavy vehicles and light passenger vehicle.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] When referring to heavy vehicles, the term is increasingly applied to mean "permanent multiple-wheel drive" on 2×2, 4×4, 6×6, or 8×8 drivetrain systems that include a differential between the front and rear drive shafts.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] This is often coupled with some sort of antislip technology, increasingly hydraulics-based, that allows differentials to spin at different speeds, but still be capable of transferring the torque from a wheel with poor traction to one with better.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Typical AWD systems work well on all surfaces, but are not intended for more extreme off-road use.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] When used to describe AWD systems in light passenger vehicles, it refers to a system that applies torque to all four wheels (permanently or on-demand) or is targeted at improving on-road traction and performance (particularly in inclement conditions), rather than for off-road applications.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Some all-wheel drive electric vehicles use one motor for each axle, thereby eliminating a mechanical differential between the front and rear axles.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] An example of this is the dual-motor variant of the Tesla Model S, which controls the torque distribution between its two motors electronically.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] According to the SAE International standard J1952, AWD is the preferred term for all the systems described above.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The standard subdivides AWD systems into three categories.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Part-time AWD systems require driver intervention to couple and decouple the secondary axle from the primarily driven axle, and these systems do not have a center differential (or similar device).
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The definition notes that part-time systems may have a low range.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Full-time AWD systems drive both front and rear axles at all times via a center (interaxle) differential.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The torque split of that differential may be fixed or variable depending on the type of center differential.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] In 2026, this system can be used on any surface at any speed.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The definition does not address the inclusion or exclusion of a low-range gear.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] On-demand AWD systems drive the secondary axle via an active or passive coupling device or "by an independently powered drive system".
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The standard notes that in some cases, the secondary drive system may also provide primary vehicle propulsion.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] An example is a hybrid all-wheel-drive (AWD) vehicle where the primary axle is driven by an internal combustion engine and the secondary axle is driven by an electric motor.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] When the internal combustion engine is shut off, the secondary, electrically driven axle becomes the only driven axle.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] On-demand systems function primarily with only one powered axle until torque is required by the second axle.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] At that point, either a passive or active coupling sends torque to the secondary axle.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Two wheels fixed to the same axle (but on the opposite axle ends) need to turn at different speeds as a vehicle goes around a curve.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The reason is that the wheel that is located on the inner side of the curve needs to travel less distance than the opposite wheel for the same duration of time.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] However, if both wheels are connected to the same axle driveshaft, they always have to spin at the same speed relative to each other.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] When going around a curve, this either forces one of the wheels to slip, if possible, to balance the apparent distance covered, or creates uncomfortable and mechanically stressful wheel hop.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] To prevent this, the wheels are allowed to turn at different speeds using a mechanical or hydraulic differential.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] This allows one driveshaft to independently drive two output shafts, axles that go from the differential to the wheel, at different speeds.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The differential does this by distributing angular force (in the form of torque) evenly, while distributing angular velocity (turning speed) such that the average for the two output shafts is equal to that of the differential ring gear.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] When powered, each axle requires a differential to distribute power between the left and right sides.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] When power is distributed to all four wheels, a third or 'center' differential can be used to distribute power between the front and rear axles.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The described system handles extremely well, as it is able to accommodate various forces of movement and distribute power evenly and smoothly, making slippage less likely.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] If the left front wheel of a 4WD vehicle slips on an icy patch of road, for instance, the slipping wheel spins faster than the other wheels due to the lower traction at that wheel.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Since a differential applies equal torque to each half-shaft, power is reduced at the other wheels, even if they have good traction.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] This problem can happen in both 2WD and 4WD vehicles, whenever a driven wheel is placed on a surface with little traction or raised off the ground.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The simplistic design works acceptably well for 2WD vehicles.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] It is much less acceptable for 4WD vehicles, because 4WD vehicles have twice as many wheels with which to lose traction, increasing the likelihood that it may happen.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] 4WD vehicles may also be more likely to be driven on surfaces with reduced traction.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] However, because torque is divided between four wheels rather than two, each wheel receives roughly half the torque of a 2WD vehicle, reducing the potential for wheel slip.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Many open differentials have no way of limiting the amount of engine power that gets sent to their attached output shafts.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] As a result, if a tire loses traction on acceleration, either because of a low-traction situation (e.g., driving on gravel or ice) or because the engine power overcomes available traction, the tire that is not slipping receives little or no power from the engine.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] In very low-traction situations, this can prevent the vehicle from moving at all.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] To overcome this, several designs of differentials can either limit the amount of slip (these are called 'limited-slip' differentials) or temporarily lock the two output shafts together to ensure that engine power reaches all driven wheels equally.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Locking differentials work by temporarily locking together a differential's output shafts, causing all wheels to turn at the same rate, providing torque in case of slippage.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] This is generally used for the center differential, which distributes power between the front and the rear axles.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] While a drivetrain that turns all wheels equally would normally fight the driver and cause handling problems, this is not a concern when wheels are slipping.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] A fairly recent innovation in automobiles is electronic traction control.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] It typically uses a vehicle's braking system to slow a spinning wheel.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] This forced slowing emulates the function of a limited-slip differential, and by using the brakes more aggressively to ensure wheels are being driven at the same speed, can also emulate a locking differential.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] This technique normally requires wheel sensors to detect when a wheel is slipping, and only activates when wheel slip is detected.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Therefore, typically no mechanism exists to actively prevent wheel slip (i.e., locking the differential in advance of wheel slip is not possible); rather, the system is designed to expressly permit wheel slip to occur, and then to attempt to send torque to the wheels with the best traction.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] If preventing all-wheel slip is a requirement, this is a limiting design.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The architecture of an AWD/4WD system can be described by showing its possible operating modes.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] A single vehicle may have the ability to operate in multiple modes depending on driver selection.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] In addition to these basic modes, some implementations can combine these modes.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The system could have a clutch across the center differential, for example, capable of modulating the front axle torque from a full-time mode with the 30:70 torque split of the center differential to the 0:100 torque split of the 2WD mode.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] In 1893, before the establishment of the modern automotive industry, English engineer Bramah Joseph Diplock patented a four-wheel drive system for a steam-powered traction engine, including four-wheel steering and three differentials, which was subsequently built.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The development also incorporated Diplock's Pedrail wheel system in what was one of the first four-wheel drive automobiles to display an intentional ability to travel on challenging road surfaces.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] It stemmed from Diplock's previous idea of developing a *road-going* steam engine that would reduce the amount of damage to public roads.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Ferdinand Porsche (senior) designed and built a four-wheel-driven electric vehicle while at the *k.u.k.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Hofwagenfabrik Ludwig Lohner & Co.* in Vienna in 1899, which was presented to the public at the 1900 Paris World's Fair.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Trained as an electrical engineer, the young Porsche was hired by a maker of commercial carriages to design and lead the manufacture of the first "horseless carriages" for Lohner.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] However, despite Porsche's ingenious hybrid drive, which basically only required two extra motors and power cables, to achieve four-wheel drive (or perhaps All-wheel drive), the car was still clumsily heavy.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Due to their unusual status, neither Diplock's on-road steam-engine, despite pioneering the center, front and rear differential drivetrain, nor the hybrid *Lohner–Porsche* is often given credit as the first four-wheel-driven automobiles.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The world's first four-wheel drive car directly powered by an internal-combustion engine, and the first with a front-engine, four-wheel-drive layout, was the Dutch *Spyker 60 H.P.*.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Commissioned for the Paris to Madrid race of 1903, it was presented that year by brothers Jacobus and Hendrik-Jan Spijker of Amsterdam.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The two-seat sports car featured permanent four-wheel drive and was also the first car equipped with a six-cylinder engine, as well as four-wheel braking.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Later used as a hill-climb racer, it is now an exhibit in the Louwman Museum (the former Nationaal Automobiel Museum) in the Hague, the Netherlands.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Designs for four-wheel drive in America first came from the Twyford Motor Car Company.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The Reynolds-Alberta Museum has a four-wheel-drive vehicle, named "Michigan", from 1905 in unrestored storage.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The first four-wheel-drive vehicles to go into mass production were built by (what became) the American Four Wheel Drive Auto Company (FWD) of Wisconsin, founded in 1908.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] (not to be confused with the term "FWD" as an initialism for *front-wheel-drive*) Along with the 11⁄2- and 2-ton Nash Quad (see below), the 3-ton FWD Model B became a standard military four-wheel-drive truck for the U.S.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Some 16,000 FWD Model B trucks were built for the British and American armies during World War I – about half by FWD and the rest by other licensed manufacturers.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Only about 20% of the trucks built were four-wheel drives, but the 4×4s were more often on the front lines.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] About 11,500 of the Jeffery / Nash Quad trucks were built for similar use between 1913 and 1919.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The Quad not only came with four-wheel-drive and four-wheel brakes, but also featured four-wheel steering.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The Quad was one of the first successful four-wheel drive vehicles ever to be made, and its production continued for 15 years with a total of 41,674 units made by 1928.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Daimler-Benz also has a history in four-wheel drive.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] After the Daimler Motoren Gesellschaft had built a four-wheel-driven vehicle called *Dernburg-Wagen*, also equipped with four-wheel steering, in 1907.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] This was used by German colonial civil servant, Bernhard Dernburg, in Namibia.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] In 1926 Mercedes and BMW introduced the sophisticated the G1, the G4, and G4 four-wheel drive vehicles.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Mercedes and BMW developed this further in 1937.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The American Marmon-Herrington Company was founded in 1931 to serve the growing market at the time for moderately priced four-wheel-drive vehicles.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The early Marmon-Herringtons proved to be the exception to the rule—4WD cars and trucks developed in the 1930s were mainly built for governments, with (future) warfare applications in mind.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Dodge developed its first four-wheel-drive truck in 1934—a military 1+1⁄2 ton designated K-39-X-4(USA), of which 796 units were built for the U.S.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Timken supplied front axles and transfer cases, added to militarized a civilian truck.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The Timken transfer case was the first *part-time* design, that allowed the driver to engage or disengage four-wheel drive using a lever inside the cab.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] In spite of the limited 1930s U.S. military budgets, the '34 truck was liked well-enough that a more modern 1+1⁄2 ton truck was developed, and 1,700 RF-40-X-4(USA) trucks were produced in 1938, and 292 TF-40-X-4(USA) in 1939.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Starting in 1936, Japanese company Tokyu Kurogane Kogyo built roughly 4,700 four-wheel-drive roadsters, called the Kurogane Type 95 reconnaissance car, used by the Imperial Japanese Army from 1937 until 1944, during the Second Sino-Japanese War.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Three different bodystyles were manufactured – a two-door roadster, a two-door pickup truck, and a four-door phaeton, all equipped with a transfer case that engaged the front wheels, powered by a 1.3-litre, two-cylinder, air-cooled OHV V-twin engine.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The 1937 Mercedes-Benz G5 and BMW 325 4×4 featured full-time four-wheel drive, four-wheel steering, three locking differentials, and fully independent suspension.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] They were produced because of a government demand for a four-wheel-drive passenger vehicle.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The modern Geländewagen such as the Mercedes-Benz G-Class still feature some of the attributes, with the exception of fully independent suspension, since it can compromise ground clearance.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The Unimog is also a result of Mercedes 4×4 technology.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The first Russian-produced four-wheel-drive vehicle, also in part for civilian use, was the GAZ-61, developed in the Soviet Union in 1938.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] "Civilian use" may be a bit of a misnomer, as most, if not all, were used by the Soviet government and military (as command cars), but the GAZ-61-73 version is the first four-wheel-drive vehicle with a normal closed sedan body.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Elements of the chassis were used in subsequent military vehicles such as the 1940 GAZ-64 and the 1943 GAZ-67, as well as the postwar GAZ-69, and the properly civilian GAZ-M-72, based on the rear-wheel drive GAZ-20 "Victory" and built from 1955 to 1958.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Until "go-anywhere" vehicles were needed for the military on a large scale, four-wheel drive and all-wheel-drive vehicles had not found their place.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The World War II Jeep, originally developed by American Bantam, but mass-produced by Willys and Ford, became the best-known four-wheel-drive vehicle in the world during the war.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The American Dodge WC series and Chevrolet G506 4×4 variants were also produced by the hundreds of thousands, as well as the Canadian Military Pattern trucks, of which 4×4s were by far the most prevalent of their various driveline configurations.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Availability of certain critical components, such as transfer cases and especially constant-velocity joints affected development.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Though not used much on commercial vehicles, all-wheel drive vehicles all needed these; and they would use two or three times the number of driven axles, meaning more gears to cut for all the differentials.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Produced up to the war by a few specialized firms with limited capacity, from spring 1942, Ford, Dodge, and Chevrolet joined in fabricating these in a quantity more than 100-fold greater than in 1939.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Although Russia had its own jeep-like vehicle (the GAZ-64) up and running in 1940, a year earlier than the American jeep, in the early years of the war, they relied significantly on Lend-Lease vehicles, provided by the western allies.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] In 1943, they launched a further-developed version: the GAZ-67.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] By contrast, the Axis powers' closest equivalent to the jeep, the VW Kübelwagen, of which only some 50,000 were built, though being equipped with portal gear hubs, only had rear-wheel drive.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Willys introduced the model CJ-2A in 1945, the first full-production four-wheel-drive vehicle for sale in the general marketplace.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Due to the ubiquitous World War II Jeep's success, its rugged utilitarianism set the pattern for many four-wheel-drive vehicles to come.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Dodge also started production of the civilian 4WD Power Wagon trucks, for the 1946 model year.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Both the Willys and the Dodge were developed directly from their WW II predecessors.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Equally boxy to the Jeep, and also inline-four powered, the Land Rover appeared at the Amsterdam Motor Show in 1948.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Originally conceived as a stop-gap product for the struggling Rover car company, despite chronic underinvestment, it succeeded far better than their passenger cars.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Inspired by a Willys MB – the ubiquitous WWII "jeep" – that was frequently run off-road on the farm belonging to chief engineer Maurice Wilks, Land Rover developed the more refined yet still off-road capable luxury 4WD Range Rover in the 1970s.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] With the acquisition of the "Jeep" name in 1950, Willys had cornered the brand.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Its successor, Kaiser Jeep, introduced a revolutionary 4WD wagon called the Wagoneer in 1963.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Not only was it technically innovative, with independent front suspension and the first automatic transmission coupled to 4WD, but also it was equipped and finished as a regular passenger automobile.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] In effect, it was the ancestor of the modern SUV.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The luxury AMC or Buick V8-powered Super Wagoneer produced from 1966 to 1969 raised the bar even higher.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Jensen applied the Formula Ferguson (FF) full-time all-wheel-drive system to 318 units of their Jensen FF built from 1966 to 1971, marking the first time 4WD was used in a production GT sports car.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] While most 4WD systems split torque evenly, the Jensen split torque roughly 40% front, 60% rear by gearing the front and rear at different ratios.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] American Motors Corporation (AMC) acquired Kaiser's Jeep Division in 1970 and quickly upgraded and expanded the entire line of off-road 4WD vehicles.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] With its added roadworthiness, the top-range full-sized Grand Wagoneer continued to compete with traditional luxury cars.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Partially hand-built, it was relatively unchanged during its production through 1991, even after Chrysler's buyout of AMC.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Subaru introduced the category-expanding Leone in 1972, an inexpensive compact station wagon with a light-duty, part-time four-wheel-drive system that could not be engaged on dry pavement.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] In September, AMC introduced Quadra Trac full-time AWD for the 1973 model year Jeep Cherokee and Wagoneer.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Due to full-time AWD, which relieved the driver of getting out to lock hubs and having to manually select between 2WD and 4WD modes, it dominated all other makes in FIA rally competition.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Gene Henderson and Ken Pogue won the Press-on-Regardless Rally FIA championship with a Quadra Trac-equipped Jeep in 1972.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] American Motors introduced the innovative Eagle for the 1980 model year.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] These were the first American mass-production cars to use the complete front-engine, four-wheel-drive system.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The AMC Eagle was offered as a sedan, coupe, and station wagon with permanent automatic all-wheel drive passenger models.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The new Eagles combined Jeep technology with an existing and proven AMC passenger automobile platform.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] They ushered a whole new product category of "sport-utility" or crossover SUV.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] AMC's Eagles came with the comfort and high-level appointments expected of regular passenger models and used the off-road technology for an extra margin of safety and traction.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The Eagle's thick viscous fluid center differential provided a quiet and smooth transfer of power that was directed proportionally to the axle with the greatest traction.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] This was a true full-time system operating only in four-wheel drive without undue wear on suspension or driveline components.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] No low range was used in the transfer case.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] This became the forerunner of the designs that followed from other manufacturers.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The automobile press at the time tested the traction of the Eagles and described it as far superior to the Subaru's and that it could beat many so-called off-road vehicles.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The Eagles were popular (particularly in the snowbelt), had towing capacity, and came in several equipment levels including sport and luxury trims.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Two additional models were added in 1981, the subcompact SX/4 and Kammback.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] A manual transmission and a front axle-disconnect feature were also made available for greater fuel economy.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] During 1981 and 1982, a unique convertible was added to the line.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The Eagle's monocoque body was reinforced for the conversion and had a steel targa bar with a removable fiberglass roof section.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The Eagle station wagon remained in production for one model year after Chrysler acquired AMC in 1987.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Total AMC Eagle production was almost 200,000 vehicles.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Audi also introduced a permanently all-wheel-driven road-going car, the Audi Quattro, in 1980.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Audi's chassis engineer, Jörg Bensinger, had noticed in winter tests in Finland that a vehicle used by the West German Army, the Volkswagen Iltis, could beat any high-performance Audi.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] He proposed developing a four-wheel-drive car that would also be used for rallying to improve Audi's conservative image.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The Audi quattro system became a feature on production cars.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] In 1987, Toyota also developed a car built for competition in rally campaigns.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] A limited number of road-going FIA Homologation Special Vehicle Celica GT-Four (known as Toyota Celica All-Trac Turbo in North America) were produced.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The All-Trac system was later available on serial production Toyota Camry, Toyota Corolla, and Toyota Previa models.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Some of the earliest mid-engined four-wheel-drive cars were the various road-legal rally cars made for Group B homologation, such as the Ford RS200 made from 1984 to 1986.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] In 1989, niche maker Panther Westwinds created a mid-engined four-wheel drive, the Panther Solo 2.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] In the United States, as of late 2013, AWD vehicles comprised 32% of new light vehicle sales, up 5% since 2008.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] This is in large part due to the popularity of the crossover.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Most crossovers offer the popular technology, in spite of it increasing vehicle price and fuel consumption.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Car manufacturers have inundated consumers with marketing proclaiming AWD as a safety feature, although the advantage of AWD over FWD occurs in accelerating, not braking or steering.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Tests have shown that though AWD gives improved acceleration in wintery conditions, it does not help with braking.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] In 2008, Nissan introduced the GT-R featuring a rear-mounted transaxle.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The AWD system requires two drive shafts, one main shaft from the engine to the transaxle and differential and a second drive shaft from the transaxle to the front wheels.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Spyker is credited with building and racing the first four-wheel-drive racing car, the Spyker 60 HP in 1903.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Bugatti created a total of three four-wheel-drive racers, the Type 53, in 1932, but the cars were notorious for having poor handling.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Miller produced the first 4WD car to qualify for the Indianapolis 500, the 1938 Miller Gulf Special.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Ferguson Research Ltd. built the front-engined P99 Formula One car that actually won a non-World Championship race with Stirling Moss in 1961.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] In 1968, Team Lotus raced cars in the Indy 500 and three years later in Formula 1 with the Lotus 56, that had both turbine engines and 4WD, as well as the 1969 4WD-Lotus 63 that had the standard 3-litre V8 Ford Cosworth engine.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Matra also raced a similar MS84, and McLaren entered their M9A in the British Grand Prix, while engine manufacturers Cosworth produced their own version, which was tested but never raced.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] All these F1 cars were considered inferior to their RWD counterparts, as the advent of aerodynamic downforce meant that adequate traction could be obtained in a lighter and more mechanically efficient manner, and the idea was discontinued, though Lotus tried repeatedly.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Nissan and Audi had success with all-wheel drive in road racing with the former's advent of the Nissan Skyline GT-R in 1989.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] So successful was the car that it dominated the Japanese circuit for the first years of production, going on to bigger and more impressive wins in Australia before weight penalties eventually levied a*de facto*ban on the car.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Most controversial was the win pulled off at the 1990 Macau Grand Prix, where the car led from start to finish.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Audi's dominance in the Trans-Am Series in 1988 was equally controversial, as it led to a weight penalty midseason and to a rule revision banning all AWD cars; its dominance in Super Touring eventually led to a FIA ban on AWD system in 1998.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] New 2011 24 Hours of Le Mans regulations may revive AWD/4WD in road racing, though such systems are only allowed in new hybrid-powered Le Mans prototypes.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] One example is the Audi R18 e-tron quattro (winner of 2012 race, the first hybrid/4WD to win Le Mans), using an electric motor in the front axle with the gasoline engine in the rear.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Medium-duty and heavy-duty trucks have recently adopted 4×4 drivetrains; 4×4 medium-duty trucks became common after Ford began selling Ford Super Duty trucks.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] These trucks shared many parts between the light-duty and medium-duty, reducing production costs.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The Dana 60 front axle is used on both medium- and light-duty Super Duty trucks.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Furthermore, the Big Three share/shared parts between the companies, reducing costs.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The Dana S 110 is currently being used for the rear drive, under Ford and Ram's medium-duty trucks.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The Dana 110 was also used on the General Motors 4×4s.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Ram Trucks began selling medium-duty trucks, 4×4 and 4×2, in 2008.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] General Motors sold a 4×4 for model years 2005–2009.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Volvo introduced the Model 646 four-wheel-drive backhoe loader in 1977.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] In engineering terms, "four-wheel drive" designates a vehicle with power delivered to four wheel ends spread over at least two axles.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The term "4×4" (pronounced *four by four*) was in use to describe North American military four-wheel-drive vehicles as early as the 1940s, with the first number indicating the number of wheel ends on a vehicle and the second indicating the number of driven wheels.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Trucks with dual tires on the rear axle and two driven axles are designated as 4×4s despite having six wheels, because the paired rear wheels behave as a single wheel for traction and classification purposes.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] True 6×6 vehicles, which have three powered axles, are classified as 6×6s regardless of how many wheels they have.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Examples of these with two rear, one front axle are the six-wheeled Pinzgauer, which is popular with defense forces around the globe, and 10-wheeled GMC CCKW made famous by the U.S.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Four-wheeler is a related term applying to all-terrain vehicles, and not to be confused with four-wheel drive.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The "four" in the instance referring to the vehicle having four wheels, not necessarily all driven.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Prompted by a perceived need for a simple, inexpensive all-terrain vehicle for oil exploration in North Africa, French motor manufacturer Citroën developed the 2CV Sahara in 1958.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Unlike other 4×4 vehicles, which use a conventional transfer case to drive the front and rear axles, the Sahara had two engines, each independently driving a separate axle, with the rear engine facing backwards.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The two throttles, clutches, and gear-change mechanisms could be linked, so the two 12 hp (9 kW) 425 cc (26 cu in) engines could run together, or they could be split and the car driven solely by either engine.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Combined with twin fuel tanks and twin batteries (which could be set up to run either or both engines), the redundancy of two separate drive trains meant that they could make it back to civilization even after major mechanical failures.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Only around 700 of these cars were built, and only 27 are known to exist today.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] BMC experimented with a twin-engined Mini Moke (dubbed the "Twini Moke") in the mid-1960s, but never put it into production.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] This made advantage of the Mini's 'power pack' layout, with a transverse engine and the gearbox in the engine sump.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Simply by fitting a second engine/gearbox unit across the rear, a rudimentary 4×4 system could be produced.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Early prototypes had separate gear levers and clutch systems for each engine.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Later versions sent for evaluation by the British Army had more user-friendly linked systems.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Chadwick patented a 4WD system, GB 1113068, that used hemispherical wheels for an all-terrain vehicle.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Warne, patented, GB 2172558, an improvement on Chadwick's design that did not use differential gear assemblies.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] By using near-spherical wheels with the provision to tilt and turn each wheel co-ordinatively, the driven wheels maintain constant traction.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Furthermore, all driven wheels steer, and as pairing of wheels is not necessary, vehicles with an odd number of wheels are possible without affecting the system's integrity.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Progressive deceleration is made possible by dynamically changing the front-to-rear effective wheel diameter ratios.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Volkswagen Motorsport, with the help of Austrian company Kaimann Racing for the development, used a twin engine Golf Mk2 for the 1985, 1986 and 1987 Pikes Peak International Hill Climb.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Suzuki Motors introduced the Suzuki Escudo Pikes Peak Edition in 1996.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Earlier Suzuki versions were twin-engined; from 1996 on, the engine is a twin-turbocharged 2.0-L V6, mated to a sequential six-speed manual transmission.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Nissan Motors has developed a system called E-4WD, designed for cars that are normally front-wheel drive; however, the rear wheels are powered by electric motors.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] This system was introduced in some variants of the Nissan Cube and Tiida.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Chrysler's Jeep Division debuted the twin-engined, 670 hp (500 kW) Jeep Hurricane concept at the 2005 North American International Auto Show in Detroit.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] This vehicle has a unique "crab crawl" capability, which allows it to rotate 360° in place.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] This is accomplished by driving the left wheels as a pair and the right wheels as a pair, as opposed to driving the front and rear pairs.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] A central gearbox allows one side to drive in the opposite direction from the other.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Some hybrid vehicles such as the Lexus RX400h provide power to an AWD system through a pair of electric motors, one to the front wheels and one to the rear.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Transfer of power is managed automatically by internal electronics based on traction conditions and need, making this an all-wheel-drive system.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The 4RM system used in the Ferrari FF and Purosangue is unique in that it has a rear transaxle with a secondary front transaxle connected directly to the engine.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The car operates primarily as a rear-wheel drive vehicle.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Clutches in the front transaxle engage when the rear wheels slip.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Drive to the front wheels is transmitted through two infinitely variable clutch packs that are allowed to 'slip' to give the required road wheel speeds.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The front transaxle has three gears, two forward, and reverse.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The two forward gears of the front transmission match the lower four forward gears of the rear transmission.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] The connection between this gearbox and each front wheel is via independent Haldex-type clutches, without a differential.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] Due to the difference in ratios, the clutches continually slip and only transmit, at most, 20% of the engine's torque.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] In the late 1970's, International Harvester developed a low cost substitute for four-wheel drive.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p01] They used two 2wd rear ends from their model 1086 tractors and coupled them together in their new model 3588 tractor. because this system had no transfer case and was just two 2wd systems joined together, the system was dubbed the "2+2".
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p02] The above systems ending with "#" function by selectively using the traction control system (via ABS) to brake a slipping wheel.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p02] Note: the above all function like 2WD when the multi-plate clutch coupling is not engaged (with exception of Subaru models), and like 4WD high-range in a part-time 4WD system when the clutch is engaged (usually by computer although some allow manual control).
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p02] Some in this category have varying degrees of control in the torque distribution between front and rear by allowing some of the clutches in a multi-plate clutch coupling to engage and slip varying amounts.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p02] An example of a system like this is the BorgWarner i-Trac(TM) system.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p02] Note: the Haldex Traction-based car list was created from the list on Haldex Traction corporate website: Haldex Cars.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p02] A version of the BorgWarner ITM3e system is used on 2006 and up Porsche 911TT's.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p02] The Borg-Warner ITM 3e is also used in the 2006-now Hyundai Santa Fe and the Hyundai Tucson.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p02] In the Hyundais, the ITM 3e acts like a full-time AWD with 95:5 normal torque split.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p02] In extreme conditions, the system can be locked in a 50:50 split via the 4WD LOCK button.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p02] These are vehicles that have no center differential.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p02] Since there is no center differential to allow for speed differences between the front and rear wheels when turning, a small amount of tire slippage must occur during turns.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p02] When used on slick surfaces, this is not a problem, but when turning on dry pavement, the tires grip, then are forced to slip, then grip again, and so on, until the turn is completed.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p02] This causes the vehicle to exhibit a 'hopping' or 'binding' sensation.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p02] Using an engaged part-time 4WD system on a hard surface is not recommended, as damage to the drive-line eventually occurs.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p02] Part-time transfer cases are the industry standard transfer case for the 4×4 truck market.
[src:aeolian-processes/4x4-vehicles-p02] Any other transfer case can be considered more robust, however more moving parts and complexity can, sometimes, make other transfer cases less durable.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] Abrasion, under its strictest definition, is commonly confused with attrition and sometimes hydraulic action however, the latter less commonly so.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] Both abrasion and attrition refers to the wearing down of an object.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] Abrasion occurs as a result of two surfaces rubbing against each other, resulting in the wearing down of one or both of the surfaces.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] However, attrition refers to the breaking off of particles (erosion) which occurs as a result of objects hitting against each other.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] Abrasion leads to surface-level destruction over a period of time, whereas attrition results in more change at a faster rate.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] Today, the geomorphology community uses the term "abrasion" in a looser way, often interchangeably with the term "wear".
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] Abrasion in a stream or river channel occurs when the sediment carried by a river scours the bed and banks, contributing significantly to erosion.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] In terms of a glacier, it is a similar principal; the moving of rocks over a surface wears it away with friction, digging a channel that, when the glacier moves away, is called a U-shaped valley.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] Bedload transport consists of mostly larger clasts, which cannot be picked up by the velocity of the streamflow, rolling, sliding, and/or saltating (bouncing) downstream along the bed.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] Suspended load typically refers to smaller particles, such as silt, clay, and finer grain sands uplifted by processes of sediment transport.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] Grains of various sizes and composition are transported differently in terms of the threshold flow velocities required to dislodge and deposit them, as is modeled in the Hjulström curve.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] These grains polish and scour the bedrock and banks when they make abrasive contact.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] Coastal abrasion occurs as breaking ocean waves containing a sand and larger fragments erode the shoreline or headland.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] The hydraulic action of waves contributes heavily.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] This removes material, resulting in undercutting and possible collapse of unsupported overhanging cliffs.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] This erosion can threaten structure or infrastructure on coastlines, and the impact will very likely increase as global warming increases sea level rise.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] Seawalls are sometimes built-in defense, but in many locations, conventional coastal engineering solutions such as sea walls are increasingly challenged and their maintenance may become unsustainable due to changes in climate conditions, sea-level rise, land subsidence, and sediment supply.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] Abrasion platforms are shore platforms where wave action abrasion is a prominent process.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] If it is currently being fashioned, it will be exposed only at low tide, but there is a possibility that the wave-cut platform will be hidden sporadically by a mantle of beach shingle (the abrading agent).
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] If the platform is permanently exposed above the high-water mark, it is probably a raised beach platform, which is not considered a product of abrasion but may be undercut by abrasion as sea level rises.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] Glacial abrasion is the surface wear achieved by individual clasts, or rocks of various sizes, contained within ice or by subglacial sediment as the glacier slides over bedrock.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] Abrasion can crush smaller grains or particles and remove grains or multigrain fragments, but the removal of larger fragments is classified as plucking (or quarrying), the other major erosion source from glaciers.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] Plucking creates the debris at the base or sides of the glacier that causes abrasion.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] While plucking has generally been thought of as a greater force of geomorphological change, there is evidence that in softer rocks with wide joint spacing that abrasion can be just as efficient.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] A smooth, polished surface is left behind by glacial abrasion, sometimes with glacial striations, which provide information about the mechanics of abrasion under temperate glaciers.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] Much consideration has been given to the role of wind as an agent of geomorphological change on Earth and other planets (Greely & Iversen 1987).
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] Aeolian processes involve wind eroding materials, such as exposed rock, and moving particles through the air to contact other materials and deposit them elsewhere.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] These forces are notably similar to models in fluvial environments.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] Aeolian processes demonstrate their most notable consequences in arid regions of sparse and abundant unconsolidated sediments, such as sand.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] There is now evidence that bedrock canyons, landforms traditionally thought to evolve only from the fluvial forces of flowing water, may indeed be extended by the aeolian forces of wind, perhaps even amplifying bedrock canyon incision rates by an order of magnitude above fluvial abrasion rates.
[src:aeolian-processes/abrasion-geology] Redistribution of materials by wind occurs at multiple geographic scales and can have important consequences for regional ecology and landscape evolution.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Dust in homes is composed of about 20–50% dead skin cells.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] The rest, and in offices and other built environments, is composed of small amounts of plant pollen, human hairs, animal fur, textile fibers, paper fibers, minerals from outdoor soil, burnt meteorite particles, and many other materials which may be found in the local environment.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Atmospheric or wind-borne fugitive dust, also known as *aeolian dust*, comes from dry regions where high-speed winds can remove mostly silt-sized material, abrading susceptible surfaces.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] This includes areas where grazing, ploughing, vehicle use, and other human behaviors have further destabilized the land, though not all source areas have been largely affected by anthropogenic impacts.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Dust-producing surfaces cover one-third of the global land area.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] These are made up of hyper-arid regions like the Sahara, which covers 0.9 billion hectares, and drylands, which occupy 5.2 billion hectares.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Dust in the atmosphere is produced by saltation and abrasive sandblasting of sand-sized grains, and it is transported through the troposphere.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] This airborne dust is considered an aerosol, and once in the atmosphere, it can produce strong local radiative forcing.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Saharan dust, in particular, can be transported and deposited as far as the Caribbean and the Amazon basin and may affect air temperature, cause ocean cooling, and alter rainfall amounts.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Dust in the Middle East has been a historic phenomenon.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Recently, because of climate change and the escalating process of desertification, the problem has worsened dramatically.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] As a multi-factor phenomenon, there is not yet a clear consensus on the sources or potential solutions to the problem.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] The dust in Iraq and Iran are migratory systems that move from west to east and have the highest intensity, concentration, and extent until mid-summer, then reverse and flow from east to west in the spring.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] The causes of their occurrence are the lack of humidity, dry environment, low rainfall, and annual droughts.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Due to the decrease of rainfall in areas such as Iraq and Syria, most of the dust in Iran also originates from the regions of Iraq, Syria, and Jordan.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] In addition to the foreign foci, there are areas inside the country that have either formed new dust foci in recent years or were from the past and their extent has increased.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Among these areas, parts of southern Tehran, south of Alborz province – which in the past were plains, riverbeds, seasonal lakes, and seasonal reservoirs – and Gavkhoni wetland of Isfahan province can be mentioned because they have become dry and prone to dust.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] In Iran, the dust directly affects more than 5 million people and has become a serious government issue recently.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] In the Khuzestan province, it has led to the severe increase of air pollution.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] The amount of pollutants in the air has surpassed more than 50 times the normal level several times in a year.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Recently, initiatives such as Project-Dust have been established to study dust in the Middle East directly.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] The continuation of drought has caused water scarcity or drying up of some wetlands and lakes such as Hamon and Urmia Lake.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] This has turned them into centers of dust.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Dust kicked up by vehicles traveling on roads is a significant source of harmful air pollution.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Road dust consists of deposits of vehicle and industrial exhaust gas, particles from tire and brake wear, dust from paved roads or potholes, and dust from construction sites.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Road dust is a significant contributor to the generation and release of particulates into the atmosphere.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Control of road dust is a significant challenge in urban areas, and also in other locations with high levels of vehicular traffic upon unsealed roads, such as mines and landfills.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] "Engine exhaust emissions, especially from those operating on diesel fuel, can be a significant source of fine particle generation from construction sites." Construction and demolition activities can also produce a large amount of construction waste.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] The dust and particulates can become fugitive and airborne with vehicle movements both on and outside the sites, especially when it is windy and dry.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Road dust may be suppressed by mechanical methods like street sweeper, vehicles equipped with vacuum cleaners, vegetable oil sprays, or with water sprayers.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Improvements in automotive engineering have reduced the amount of PM10s produced by road traffic; the proportion representing re-suspension of existing particulates has increased as a result.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Coal dust is responsible for the respiratory disease known as pneumoconiosis, including coal worker's pneumoconiosis disease that occurs among coal miners.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] The danger of coal dust resulted in environmental law regulating workplace air quality in some jurisdictions.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] In addition, if enough coal dust is dispersed within the air in a given area, in very rare circumstances, it can cause a dust explosion.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] These circumstances are typically within confined spaces.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Most governmental Environmental Protection Agencies, including the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) mandate that facilities that generate fugitive dust, minimize or mitigate the production of dust in their operation.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] The most frequent dust control violations occur at new residential housing developments in urban areas.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] United States federal law requires that construction sites obtain planning permissions to conduct earth moving and clearing of areas, so that plans to control dust emissions while the work is being carried out are specified.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Control measures include such simple practices as spraying construction and demolition sites with water, and preventing the tracking of dust onto adjacent roads.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] US federal laws require dust control on sources such as vacant lots, unpaved parking lots, and dirt roads.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Dust in such places may be suppressed by mechanical methods, including paving or laying down gravel, or stabilizing the surface with water, vegetable oils or other dust suppressants, or by using water misters to suppress dust that is already airborne.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Dust control is the suppression of solid particles with diameters less than 500 micrometers (*i.e.* half a millimeter).
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Dust poses a health risk to children, older people, and those with respiratory diseases.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Care is required when removing dust to avoid causing the dust to become airborne.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] A feather duster tends to agitate the dust so it lands elsewhere.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Certified HEPA (tested to MIL STD 282) can effectively trap 99.97% of dust at 0.3 micrometers.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Not all HEPA filters can effectively stop dust; while vacuum cleaners with HEPA filters, water, or cyclones may filter more effectively than without, they may still exhaust millions of particles per cubic foot of air circulated.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Central vacuum cleaners can be effective in removing dust, especially if they are exhausted directly to the outdoors.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Air filters differ greatly in their effectiveness.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Laser particle counters are an effective way to measure filter effectiveness; medical grade instruments can test for particles as small as 0.3 micrometers.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] In order to test for dust in the air, there are several options available.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Pre-weighed filter and matched weight filters made from polyvinyl chloride or mixed cellulose ester are suitable for respirable dust (less than 10 micrometers in diameter).
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] A dust resistant surface is a state of prevention against dust contamination or damage, by a design or treatment of materials and items in manufacturing or through a repair process .
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] A reduced tacticity of a synthetic layer or covering can protect surfaces and release small molecules that could have remained attached.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] A panel, container or enclosure with seams may feature types of strengthened structural rigidity or sealant to vulnerable edges and joins.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Cosmic dust is widely present in outer space, where gas and dust clouds are the primary precursors for planetary systems.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] The zodiacal light, as seen in a dark night sky, is produced by sunlight reflected from particles of dust in orbit around the Sun.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] The tails of comets are produced by emissions of dust and ionized gas from the body of the comet.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Dust also covers solid planetary bodies, and vast dust storms can occur on Mars which cover almost the entire planet.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Interstellar dust is found between the stars, and high concentrations produce diffuse nebulae and reflection nebulae.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Ambient radiation heats dust and re-emits radiation into the microwave band, which may distort the cosmic microwave background power spectrum.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Dust in this regime has a complicated emission spectrum and includes both thermal dust emission and spinning dust emission.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Dust samples returned from outer space have provided information about conditions of the early solar system.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Several spacecraft have sought to gather samples of dust and other materials.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Among these craft was *Stardust*, which flew past 81P/Wild in 2004, and returned a capsule of the comet's remains to Earth.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] In 2010 the Japanese *Hayabusa* spacecraft returned samples of dust from the surface of an asteroid.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Dust bunnies (or dustbunnies) are small clumps of dust that form under furniture and in corners that are not cleaned regularly.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] They are made of hair, lint, flakes of dead skin, spider webs, dust, and sometimes light rubbish and debris and are held together by static electricity and felt-like entanglement.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] They can house dust mites or other parasites and can lower the efficiency of dust filters by clogging them.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] The movement of a single large particle can start the formation of a dust bunny.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Dust bunnies are harmful to electronics because they can obstruct air flow through heat sinks, raising temperatures significantly and therefore shortening the life of electronic components.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Dust bunnies have been used as an analogy for the accretion of cosmic matter in planetoids.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] House dust mites are present indoors wherever humans live.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Positive tests for dust mite allergies are extremely common among people with asthma.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Dust mites are microscopic arachnids whose primary food is dead human skin cells, but they do not live on living people.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] They and their feces and other allergens are major constituents of house dust, but because they are so heavy they are not suspended for long in the air.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] They are generally found on the floor and other surfaces until disturbed (by walking, for example).
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] It could take between twenty minutes and two hours for dust to settle back out of the air.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Dust mites are a nesting species that prefer a dark, warm, and humid climate.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] They flourish in mattresses, bedding, upholstered furniture, and carpets.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] Their feces include enzymes that are released upon contact with a moist surface, which can happen when a person inhales, and these enzymes can kill cells within the human body.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-dust] House dust mites did not become a problem until humans began to use textiles, such as blankets and clothing.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-landform] Aeolian landforms are commonly observed in sandy deserts and on frozen lakes or sea ice and have been observed and studied around Earth and on other planets, including Mars and Pluto.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-landform] The word "aeolian" derives from Æolus, the Greek god of the winds, and the son of Hellen and the nymph Orseis, and a brother of Dorus, Xuthus and Amphictyon.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-landform] Aeolian landforms are formed when wind moves sediment (see aeolian processes).
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-landform] Sediment particles move when they are lifted by upwards Bernoulli forces that exceed their downwards weight or when they are dragged from their initial position.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-landform] Depending on the balance of these forces, particles may either creep (roll) across the surface until they settle due to a loss of velocity; hop from point to point; or be suspended entirely in the air.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-landform] These means of sediment transport can be classified as deposition, saltation, and suspension, respectively.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-landform] Once sediment transport begins, it continues via gravity and momentum.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-landform] Particles that fall out of the air typically impact the surface with enough force to dislodge further particles.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-landform] These impacts are separated in space by the saltation hop length of the traveling particles, which creates distinct areas of erosion and/or deposition.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-landform] As time passes, the surface rises in areas with net deposition, and lowers in areas with net erosion, creating initial landforms.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-landform] Larger aeolian landforms alter the surface wind field in patterns that promote their growth.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-landform] Deflation and abrasion are specific means of sediment transport than can also be attributed to aeolian processes.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-landform] Deflation, which is named for the Latin word "deflare" meaning "to blow away", refers to the scattering and removal of rock particles by wind.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-landform] Deflation occurs in deserts where diverse particles dominate the surface.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-landform] In these arid zones, sand and rock fragments are blown by jets and streams of air which remove fine grained materials from the surface and leave behind a rocky desert.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-landform] Abrasion is another mechanism of force exerted by the wind on surficial materials that is characterized by friction caused by moving particles scraping across a rock's surface and, as a result, continues to develop a land formation by removing further material.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-landform] Aeolian landforms are typically described in two categories: erosional and depositional.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-landform] Depositional landforms grow when sediment is deposited into an area faster than it is removed.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-landform] These landforms grow from snow, sand, and/or dust in areas where wind patterns trap particles.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-landform] For example, the Great Sand Dunes in Colorado grow as sand blown from a wide plain is deposited against the edge of the Sangre de Cristo mountains.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-landform] Some depositional landforms include dunes, barchan dunes, ripple marks, and loess.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-landform] Erosional landforms grow when more sediment is removed from an area faster than it is deposited.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-landform] They are widespread in hardened, wind-swept snow surfaces, such as the Antarctic Plateau: see sastrugi.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-landform] In sand and rock, they are rarely preserved except in arid regions.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-landform] Outside of arid regions, moving water - which is heavier and more erosive than wind - erases aeolian landforms.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-landform] Large basins are complex and there is often one or more non-aeolian process at work, including tectonics, glacial and alluvial forces.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-landform] There are several types of landforms associated with erosion.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The term is derived from the name of the Greek god Aeolus, the keeper of the winds.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Aeolian processes are most important in areas where there is little or no vegetation.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] However, aeolian deposits are not restricted to arid climates.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] They are also seen along shorelines; along stream courses in semiarid climates; in areas of ample sand weathered from weakly cemented sandstone outcrops; and in areas of glacial outwash.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Loess, which is silt deposited by wind, is common in humid to subhumid climates.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Much of North America and Europe are underlain by sand and loess of Pleistocene age originating from glacial outwash.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The lee (downwind) side of river valleys in semiarid regions are often blanketed with sand and sand dunes.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Examples in North America include the Platte, Arkansas, and Missouri Rivers.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Wind erodes the Earth's surface by *deflation* (the removal of loose, fine-grained particles by the turbulent action of the wind) and by *abrasion* (the wearing down of surfaces by the grinding action and sandblasting by windborne particles).
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Once entrained in the wind, collisions between particles further break them down, a process called *attrition*.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Worldwide, erosion by water is more important than erosion by wind, but wind erosion is important in semiarid and arid regions.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Wind erosion is increased by some human activities, such as the use of 4x4 vehicles.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Deflation is the lifting and removal of loose material from the surface by wind turbulence.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] It takes place by three mechanisms: traction/surface creep, saltation, and suspension.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Traction or surface creep is a process of larger grains sliding or rolling across the surface.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Saltation refers to particles bouncing across the surface for short distances.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Suspended particles are fully entrained in the wind, which carries them for long distances.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Saltation likely accounts for 50–70 % of deflation, while suspension accounts for 30–40 % and surface creep accounts for 5–25 %.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Regions which experience intense and sustained erosion are called deflation zones.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Most aeolian deflation zones are composed of desert pavement, a sheet-like surface of rock fragments that remains after wind and water have removed the fine particles.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The rock mantle in desert pavements protects the underlying material from further deflation.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Areas of desert pavement form the *regs* or stony deserts of the Sahara.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] These are further divided into rocky areas called *hamadas* and areas of small rocks and gravel called *serirs*.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Desert pavement is extremely common in desert environments.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Blowouts are hollows formed by wind deflation.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Blowouts are generally small, but may be up to several kilometers in diameter.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The smallest are mere dimples 0.3 meters (1 ft) deep and 3 meters (10 ft) in diameter.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The largest include the blowout hollows of Mongolia, which can be 8 kilometers (5 mi) across and 60 to 100 meters (200 to 400 ft) deep.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Big Hollow in Wyoming, US, extends 14 by 9.7 kilometers (9 by 6 mi) and is up to 90 meters (300 ft) deep.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Abrasion (also sometimes called *corrasion*) is the process of wind-driven grains knocking or wearing material off of landforms.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] It was once considered a major contributor to desert erosion, but by the mid-20th Century, it had come to be considered much less important.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Wind can normally lift sand only a short distance, with most windborne sand remaining within 50 centimeters (20 in) of the surface and practically none normally being carried above 2 meters (6 ft).
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Many desert features once attributed to wind abrasion, including wind caves, mushroom rocks, and the honeycomb weathering called tafoni, are now attributed to differential weathering, rainwash, deflation rather than abrasion, or other processes.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Abrasion produces polishing and pitting, grooving, shaping, and faceting of exposed surfaces.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] These are widespread in arid environments but geologically insignificant.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Polished or faceted surfaces called *ventifacts* are rare, requiring abundant sand, powerful winds, and a lack of vegetation for their formation.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] In parts of Antarctica wind-blown snowflakes that are technically sediments have also caused abrasion of exposed rocks.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Attrition is the wearing down by collisions of particles entrained in a moving fluid.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] It is effective at rounding sand grains and at giving them a distinctive *frosted* surface texture.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Collisions between windborne particles is a major source of dust in the size range of 2-5 microns.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Most of this is produced by the removal of a weathered clay coating from the grains.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Wind dominates the transport of sand and finer sediments in arid environments.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Wind transport is also important in periglacial areas, on river flood plains, and in coastal areas.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Coastal winds transport significant amounts of siliciclastic and carbonate sediments inland, while wind storms and dust storms can carry clay and silt particles great distances.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Wind transports much of the sediments deposited in deep ocean basins.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] In *ergs* (desert sand seas), wind is very effective at transporting grains of sand size and smaller.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Particles are transported by winds through suspension, saltation (skipping or bouncing) and creeping (rolling or sliding) along the ground.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The minimum wind velocity to initiate transport is called the *fluid threshold* or *static threshold* and is the wind velocity required to begin dislodging grains from the surface.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Once transport is initiated, there is a cascade effect from grains tearing loose other grains, so that transport continues until the wind velocity drops below the *dynamic threshold* or *impact threshold*, which is usually less than the fluid threshold.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] In other words, there is hysteresis in the wind transport system.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Small particles may be held in the atmosphere in suspension.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Turbulent air motion supports the weight of suspended particles and allows them to be transported for great distances.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Wind is particularly effective at separating sediment grains under 0.05 mm in size from coarser grains as suspended particles.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Saltation is downwind movement of particles in a series of jumps or skips.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Saltation is most important for grains of up to 2 mm in size.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] A saltating grain may hit other grains that jump up to continue the saltation.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The grain may also hit larger grains (over 2 mm in size) that are too heavy to hop, but that slowly creep forward as they are pushed by saltating grains.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Surface creep accounts for as much as 25 percent of grain movement in a desert.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Vegetation is effective at suppressing aeolian transport.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Vegetation cover of as little as 15% is sufficient to eliminate most sand transport.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The size of shore dunes is limited mostly by the amount of open space between vegetated areas.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Aeolian transport from deserts plays an important role in ecosystems globally.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] For example, wind transports minerals from the Sahara to the Amazon basin.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Saharan dust is also responsible for forming red clay soils in southern Europe.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Dust storms are wind storms that have entrained enough dust to reduce visibility to less than 1 kilometer (0.6 mi).
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Most occur on the synoptic (regional) scale, due to strong winds along weather fronts, or locally from downbursts from thunderstorms.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Crops, people, and possibly even climates are affected by dust storms.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] On Earth, dust can cross entire oceans, as occurs with dust from the Sahara that reaches the Amazon Basin.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Dust storms on Mars periodically engulf the entire planet.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] When the Mariner 9 spacecraft entered its orbit around Mars in 1971, a dust storm lasting one month covered the entire planet, thus delaying the task of photo-mapping the planet's surface.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Most of the dust carried by dust storms is in the form of silt-size particles.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Deposits of this windblown silt are known as loess.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The thickest known deposit of loess, up to 350 meters (1,150 ft), is on the Loess Plateau in China.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] This very same Asian dust is blown for thousands of miles, forming deep beds in places as far away as Hawaii.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The Peoria Loess of North America is up to 40 meters (130 ft) thick in parts of western Iowa.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The soils developed on loess are generally highly productive for agriculture.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Small whirlwinds, called dust devils, are common in arid lands and are thought to be related to very intense local heating of the air that results in instabilities of the air mass.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Dust devils may be as much as one kilometer high.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Dust devils on Mars have been observed as high as 10 kilometers (6.2 mi), though this is uncommon.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Wind is very effective at separating sand from silt and clay.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] As a result, there are distinct sandy (erg) and silty (loess) aeolian deposits, with only limited interbedding between the two.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Loess deposits are found further from the original source of sediments than ergs.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] An example of this is the Sand Hills of Nebraska, US.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Here vegetation-stabilized sand dunes are found to the west and loess deposits to the east, further from the original sediment source in the Ogallala Formation at the feet of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Some of the most significant experimental measurements on aeolian landforms were performed by Ralph Alger Bagnold, a British army engineer who worked in Egypt prior to World War II.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Bagnold investigated the physics of particles moving through the atmosphere and deposited by wind.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] He recognized two basic dune types, the crescentic dune, which he called "barchan", and the linear dune, which he called longitudinal or "seif" (Arabic for "sword").
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Bagnold developed a classification scheme that included small-scale ripples and sand sheets as well as various types of dunes.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Bagnold's classification is most applicable in areas devoid of vegetation.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] In 1941, John Tilton Hack added parabolic dunes, which are strongly influenced by vegetation, to the list of dune types.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The discovery of dunes on Mars reinvigorated aeolian process research, which increasingly makes use of computer simulation.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Wind-deposited materials hold clues to past as well as to present wind directions and intensities.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] These features help us understand the present climate and the forces that molded it.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] For example, vast inactive ergs in much of the modern world attest to late Pleistocene trade wind belts being much expanded during the Last Glacial Maximum.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Ice cores show a tenfold increase in non-volcanic dust during glacial maxima.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The highest dust peak in the Vostok ice cores dates to 20 to 21 thousand years ago.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The abundant dust is attributed to a vigorous low-latitude wind system plus more exposed continental shelf due to low sea levels.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Wind-deposited sand bodies occur as ripples and other small-scale features, sand sheets, and dunes.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Wind blowing on a sand surface ripples the surface into crests and troughs whose long axes are perpendicular to the wind direction.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The average length of jumps during saltation corresponds to the wavelength, or distance between adjacent crests, of the ripples.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] In ripples, the coarsest materials collect at the crests causing inverse grading.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] This distinguishes small ripples from dunes, where the coarsest materials are generally in the troughs.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] This is also a distinguishing feature between water laid ripples and aeolian ripples.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] A *sand shadow* is an accumulation of sand on the downwind side of an obstruction, such as a boulder or an isolated patch of vegetation.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Here the sand builds up to the angle of repose (the maximum stable slope angle), about 34 degrees, then begins sliding down the *slip face* of the patch.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] A *sandfall* is a sand shadow of a cliff or escarpment.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Closely related to sand shadows are *sand drifts*.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] These form downwind of a gap between obstructions, due to the funneling effect of the obstructions on the wind.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Sand sheets are flat or gently undulating sandy deposits with only small surface ripples.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] An example is the Selima Sand Sheet in the eastern Sahara Desert, which occupies 60,000 square kilometers (23,000 sq mi) in southern Egypt and northern Sudan.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] This consists of a few feet of sand resting on bedrock.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Sand sheets are often remarkably flat and are sometimes described as *desert peneplains*.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Sand sheets are common in desert environments, particularly on the margins of dune fields, although they also occur within ergs.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Conditions that favor the formation of sand sheets, instead of dunes, may include surface cementation, a high water table, the effects of vegetation, periodic flooding, or sediments rich in grains too coarse for effective saltation.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] A dune is an accumulations of sediment blown by the wind into a mound or ridge.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] They differ from sand shadows or sand drifts in that they are independent of any topographic obstacle.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Dunes have gentle upwind slopes on the windward side.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The downwind portion of the dune, the lee slope, is commonly a steep avalanche slope referred to as a slipface.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The minimum height of a slipface is about 30 centimeters.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Wind-blown sand moves up the gentle upwind side of the dune by saltation or creep.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Sand accumulates at the brink, the top of the slipface.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] When the buildup of sand at the brink exceeds the angle of repose, a small avalanche of grains slides down the slipface.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Grain by grain, the dune moves downwind.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Linear dunes, also called longitudinal dunes or seifs, are aligned in the direction of the prevailing winds.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Transverse dunes, which include crescent dunes (barchans), are aligned perpendicular to the prevailing winds.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] More complex dunes, such as star dunes, form where the directions of the winds are highly variable.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Additional dune types arise from various kinds of topographic forcing, such as from isolated hills or escarpments.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Transverse dunes occur in areas dominated by a single direction of the prevailing wind.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] In areas where sand is not abundant, transverse dunes take the form of barchans or crescent dunes.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] These are not common, but they are highly recognizable, with a distinctive crescent shape with the tips of the crescent directed downwind.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The dunes are widely separated by areas of bedrock or reg.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Barchans migrate up to 30 meters (98 ft) per year, with the taller dunes migrating faster.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Barchans first form when some minor topographic feature creates a sand patch.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] This grows into a sand mound, and the converging streamlines of the air flow around the mound build it into the distinctive crescent shape.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Growth is ultimately limited by the carrying capacity of the wind, which as the wind becomes saturated with sediments, builds up the slip face of the dune.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Because barchans develop in areas of limited sand availability, they are poorly preserved in the geologic record.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Where sand is more abundant, transverse dunes take the form of aklé dunes, such as those of the western Sahara.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] These form a network of sinuous ridges perpendicular to the wind direction.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Aklé dunes are preserved in the geologic record as sandstone with large sets of cross-bedding and many reactivation surfaces.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Draas are very large composite transverse dunes.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] They can be up to 4,000 meters (13,000 ft) across and 400 meters (1,300 ft) high and extend lengthwise for hundreds of kilometers.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] In form, they resemble a large aklé or barchanoid dune.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] They form over a prolonged period of time in areas of abundant sand and show a complex internal structure.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Careful 3-D mapping is required to determine the morphology of a draa preserved in the geologic record.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Linear dunes can be traced up to tens of kilometers, with heights sometimes in excess of 70 meters (230 ft).
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] They are typically several hundred meters across and are spaced 1 to 2 kilometers (0.62 to 1.24 mi) apart.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] They sometimes coalesce at a Y-junction with the fork directed upwind.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] They have a sharp sinuous or en echelon crest.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] They are thought to form from a bimodal seasonal wind pattern, with a weak wind season characterized by wind directed an at acute angle to the prevailing winds of the strong wind season.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The strong wind season produces a barchan form and the weak wind season stretches this into the linear form.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Another possibility is that these dunes result from secondary flow, though the precise mechanism remains uncertain.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Complex dunes (star dunes or rhourd dunes) are characterized by having more than two slip faces.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] They consist of a central peak with radiating crests and are thought to form where strong winds can come from any direction.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Those in Gran Desierto de Altar of Mexico are thought to have formed from precursor linear dunes due to a change in the wind pattern about 3000 years ago.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Complex dunes show little lateral growth but strong vertical growth and are important sand sinks.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Vegetated parabolic dunes are crescent-shaped, but the ends of the crescent point upwind, not downwind.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] They form from the interaction of vegetation patches with active sand sources, such as blowouts.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The vegetation stabilizes the arms of the dune, and an elongated lake sometimes forms between the arms of the dune.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Clay dunes are uncommon but have been found in Africa, Australia, and along the Gulf Coast of North America.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] These form on mud flats on the margins of saline bodies of water subject to strong prevailing winds during a dry season.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Clay particles are bound into sand-sized pellets by salts and are then deposited in the dunes, where the return of the cool season allows the pellets to absorb moisture and become bound to the dune surface.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Deserts cover 20 to 25 percent of the modern land surface of the earth, mostly between the latitudes of 10 to 30 degrees north or south.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Here the descending part of the tropical atmospheric circulation (the Hadley cell) produces high atmospheric pressure and suppresses precipitation.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Large areas of this desert is floored with windblown sand.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Such areas are called *ergs* when they exceed about 125 square kilometers (48 sq mi) in area or *dune fields* when smaller.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Ergs and dune fields make up about 20% of modern deserts or about 6% of the Earth's total land surface.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The sandy areas of today's world are somewhat anomalous.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Deserts, in both the present day and in the geological record, are usually dominated by alluvial fans rather than dune fields.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The present relative abundance of sandy areas may reflect reworking of Tertiary sediments following the Last Glacial Maximum.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Most modern deserts have experienced extreme Quaternary climate change, and the sediments that are now being churned by wind systems were generated in upland areas during previous pluvial (moist) periods and transported to depositional basins by stream flow.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The sediments, already sorted during their initial fluvial transport, were further sorted by wind, which also sculpted the sediments into eolian landforms.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The state of an aeolian system depends mainly on three things: The amount of sediment supply, the availability of sediments, and the transport capacity of the winds.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The sediment supply is largely produced in pluvial periods (periods of greater rainfall) and accumulates by runoff as fan deltas or terminal fans in sedimentary basins.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Another important source of sediments is the reworking of carbonate sediments on continental shelves exposed during times of lower sea level.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Sediment availability depends on the coarseness of the local sediment supply, the degree of exposure of sediment grains, the amount of soil moisture, and the extent of vegetation coverage.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The potential transport rate of wind is usually more than the actual transport, because the sediment supply is usually insufficient to saturate the wind.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] In other words, most aeolian systems are *transport-undersaturated* (or *sediment-undersaturated*).
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Aeolian desert systems can be divided into wet, dry, or stabilized systems.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Dry systems have the water table well below the surface, where it has no stabilizing effect on sediments.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Dune shapes determine whether sediment is deposited, simply moves across surface (a *bypass* system), or erosion takes place.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Wet systems are characterized by a water table near the depositional surface, which exerts a strong control on deposition, bypass, or erosion.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Stabilized systems have significant vegetation, surface cement, or mud drapes which dominate the evolution of the system.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The Sahara shows the full range of all three types.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The movement of sediments in aeolian systems can be represented by sand-flow maps.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] These are based on meteorological observations, bedform orientations, and trends of yardangs.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] They are analogous to drainage maps, but are not as closely tied to topography, since wind can blow sand significant distances uphill.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The Sahara of North Africa is the largest hot desert in the world.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Flowlines can be traced from erg to erg, demonstrating very long transport downwind.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Satellite observations show yardangs aligned with the sandflow lines.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] All flowlines arise in the desert itself, and show indications of clockwise circulation roughly like high pressure cells.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The greatest deflation occurs in dried lake beds where trade winds form a low-level jet between the Tibesti Mountains and the Ennedi Plateau.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The flowlines eventually reach the, sea creating great plume of Saharan dust extending thousands of kilometers into the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] This creates a steady rain of silt into the ocean.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] It is estimated that 260 million tons of sediments are transported through this system each year, but the amount was much greater during the Last Glacial Maximum, based on deep-sea cores.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Mineral dust of 0.1–1 microns in size is a good shortwave radiation scatterer and has a cooling effect on climate.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Another example of an aeolian system is the arid interior of Australia.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] With few topographic barriers to sand movement, an anticlockwise wind system is traced by systems of longitudinal dunes.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The Namib and Oman ergs are fed by coastal sediments.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The Namib receives its sediments from the south through narrow deflation corridors from coast that cross more than 100 kilometers (62 mi) of bedrock to the erg.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The Oman was created by deflation of marine shelf carbonates during the last Pleistocene lowstand of the sea.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The Loess Plateau of China has been a long-term sink for sediments during the Quaternary ice age.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] It provides a record of glaciation, in the form of glacial loess layers separated by paleosols (fossil soils).
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The loess layers were desposited by a strong northwest winter monsoon, while the paleosols record the influence of a moist southeast monsoon.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The African savannah is mostly ergs deposited during the Last Glacial Maximum that are now stabilized by vegetation.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Aeolian processes can be discerned at work in the geologic record as long ago as the Precambrian.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Aeolian formations are prominent in the Paleozoic and Mesozoic of the western US.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Perhaps the best examples of aeolian processes in the geologic record are the Jurassic ergs of the western US.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] These include the Wingate Sandstone, the Navajo Sandstone, and the Page Sandstone.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Individual formations are separated by regional unconformities indicate erg stabilization.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The ergs interfingered with adjacent river systems, as with the Wingate Sandstone interfingering with the Moenave Formation and the Navajo Sandstone with the Kayenta Formation.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The Navajo and Nugget Sandstones were part of the largest erg deposit in the geologic record.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] These formations are up to 700 meters (2,300 ft) thick and are exposed over 265,000 square kilometers (102,000 sq mi).
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Their original extent was likely 2.5 times the present outcrop area.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Though once thought to possibly be marine in origin, they are now all but universally regarded as aeolian deposits.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] They are made up mostly of fine- to medium-sized quartz grains that are well-rounded and frosted, both indications of aeolian transport.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The Navajo contains huge tabular crossbed sets with sweeping foresets.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Individual crossbed sets dip at an angle of more than 20 degrees and are from 5 to 35 meters (16 to 115 ft) thick.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The formation contains freshwater invertebrate fossils and vertebrate tracks.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Slump structures (contorted bedding) are present that resemble those in modern wetted dunes.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Successive migrating dunes deposited a vertical stacking of eolian beds between interdune bounding surfaces and regional supersurfaces.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The Permian Rotliegend Group of the North Sea and north Europe contains sediments from adjacent uplands.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Erg sand bodies within the group are up to 500 meters (1,600 ft) thick.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Study of the crossbedding shows that sediments were deposited by a clockwise atmospheric cell.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Drilling core show dry and wet interdune surfaces and regional supersurfaces, and provide evidence of five or more cycles of erg expansion and contraction.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] A global rise in sea level finally drowned the erg and deposited the beds of the Weissliegend.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The Cedar Mesa Sandstone in Utah was contemporary with the Rogliegend.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] This formation records at least 12 erg sequences bounded by regional deflation supersurfaces.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] Aeolian landforms preserved in the formation range from damp sandsheet and lake paleosol (fossil soil) beds to thin, chaotically arranged dune sets to equilibrium erg construction, with dunes 300 to 400 meters (980 to 1,310 ft) wide migrating over still larger draas.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-processes] The draas survived individual climate cycles, and their interdunes were sites of barchan nucleation during arid portions of the climate cycles.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-sound] Historically, Aeolus was the Greek ruler of the winds, and the Ancient Greeks believed these sounds were the voice of Aeolus.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-sound] The earliest known observations about Aeolian sounds from a "scientific" viewpoint were made by Athanasius Kircher in 1650.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-sound] An Aeolian tone is produced when air passes over an obstacle, resulting in trailing vortices with oscillatory behavior.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-sound] These eddies can have strong periodic components, resulting in a steady tone.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-sound] This phenomenon is the main topic of aeroacoustics.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-sound] where V is the air velocity, D is the diameter of the cylinder, and ${\mbox{St}}$ is the Strouhal number, which has a value of about 0.2.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-sound] Aeolian sounds can be produced in the rigging of a sail-powered ship.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-sound] The vortex trails produced as the wind passes over a rope produce a sound with a frequency that varies with the velocity of the wind and the thickness of the rope.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-sound] Each doubling of the wind velocity results in an octave increase in the tone, allowing up to a six octave variation in a strong, gusty wind.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-sound] Ships may also carry Helmholtz resonators that amplify these sounds.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-sound] Aeolian sounds can also be heard among the openings in limestone cliffs, and from ends of, or openings in pipes.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-sound] Some songs have been written to emulate these varying wind sounds, such as the "Étude Op.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-sound] 1 (the 'Aeolian Harp Etude')" and the "The Winter Wind" by Frédéric Chopin or "Tempest" by Ludwig van Beethoven.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolian-sound] Aeolean sound was heard around San Francisco, California beginning June 5, 2020, as a consequence of high winds and new walkway slats installed on the Golden Gate Bridge.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolus] In Greek mythology, **Aiolos**, transcribed as **Aeolus** (/ˈiːələs/ ⓘ; Ancient Greek: Αἴολος [ǎi̯.olos]; Modern Greek: Αίολος [ˈe.olos] ⓘ) refers to three characters.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolus] These three are often difficult to tell apart, and even the ancient mythographers appear to have been perplexed about which Aeolus was which.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolus] Diodorus Siculus made an attempt to define each of these three (although it is clear that he also became muddled), and his opinion is followed here.
[src:aeolian-processes/aeolus] All three men named Aeolus appear to be connected genealogically, although the precise relationship, especially regarding the second and third Aeolus, is often ambiguous as their identities seem to have been merged by many ancient writers.
